256
00:22:17,210 --> 00:22:19,420
Send them down.
I want them lined up...

257
00:22:19,713 --> 00:22:22,256
just like a pretty little
chorus line.

258
00:22:23,383 --> 00:22:24,592
Look at that.

259
00:22:25,093 --> 00:22:28,262
- I can't stand this guy.
- Oh, Lord!

260
00:22:28,930 --> 00:22:31,432
Yes! Richmond, Virginia.

261
00:22:31,600 --> 00:22:32,975
Smell my ass!

262
00:22:33,185 --> 00:22:35,186
After he smells mine.

263
00:22:35,604 --> 00:22:39,315
That's a shame about your horse
coming in last and all.

264
00:22:39,524 --> 00:22:42,360
But I sure do love
that winning horse of mine, though.

265
00:22:42,569 --> 00:22:45,571
I owe that boy a big kiss
when I see him.

266
00:22:45,739 --> 00:22:49,950
Why don't you give him some of your
cigarettes instead? Lucky fuck!

267
00:22:50,243 --> 00:22:51,786
Hey, Tyrell.

268
00:22:52,120 --> 00:22:54,121
You pull infirmary duty this week?

269
00:22:55,082 --> 00:22:56,665
How's my horse doing anyway?

270
00:22:57,084 --> 00:22:58,209
Dead.

271
00:22:59,044 --> 00:23:01,253
Hadley busted his head up pretty good.

272
00:23:01,463 --> 00:23:03,631
Doc had gone home for the night.

273
00:23:04,132 --> 00:23:06,425
Poor bastard lay there
till this morning.

274
00:23:06,635 --> 00:23:09,095
By then, there wasn't nothing
we could do.

275
00:23:15,394 --> 00:23:16,685
What was his name?

276
00:23:20,065 --> 00:23:21,315
What'd you say?

277
00:23:23,235 --> 00:23:25,653
I was just wondering
if anyone knew his name.

278
00:23:26,321 --> 00:23:29,073
What the fuck do you care, new fish?

279
00:23:30,075 --> 00:23:33,202
Doesn't fucking matter
what his name was. He's dead.

280
00:23:55,267 --> 00:23:57,268
Anybody come at you yet?

281
00:23:59,396 --> 00:24:01,230
Anybody get to you yet?

282
00:24:02,899 --> 00:24:05,443
Hey, we all need friends in here.

283
00:24:05,735 --> 00:24:07,403
I could be a friend to you.

284
00:24:16,621 --> 00:24:18,038
Hard to get.

285
00:24:20,125 --> 00:24:21,625
I like that.

286
00:24:28,550 --> 00:24:31,802
Andy kept pretty much
to himself at first.

287
00:24:32,137 --> 00:24:34,096
I guess he had a lot on his mind...

288
00:24:34,556 --> 00:24:37,391
trying to adapt
to life on the inside.

289
00:24:38,101 --> 00:24:41,312
Wasn't until a month went by
before he opened his mouth...

290
00:24:41,521 --> 00:24:43,898
to say more than two words
to somebody.

291
00:24:45,066 --> 00:24:46,650
As it turned out...

292
00:24:47,110 --> 00:24:48,986
that somebody was me.

293
00:24:57,746 --> 00:24:59,538
I'm Andy Dufresne.

294
00:25:00,749 --> 00:25:02,500
Wife-killing banker.

295
00:25:04,753 --> 00:25:06,086
Why'd you do it?

296
00:25:06,505 --> 00:25:08,589
I didn't, since you ask.

297
00:25:09,174 --> 00:25:11,008
You're going to fit right in.

298
00:25:11,259 --> 00:25:13,928
Everybody in here's innocent.
Didn't you know that?

299
00:25:14,554 --> 00:25:17,765
- What you in here for?
- Didn't do it. Lawyer fucked me.

300
00:25:20,769 --> 00:25:23,354
Rumor has it you're a real cold fish.

301
00:25:23,563 --> 00:25:27,149
You think your shit smells
sweeter than most. Is that right?

302
00:25:27,359 --> 00:25:28,817
What do you think?

303
00:25:29,194 --> 00:25:32,279
To tell you the truth,
I haven't made up my mind.

304
00:25:33,406 --> 00:25:36,200
I understand you're a man
that knows how to get things.

305
00:25:37,160 --> 00:25:40,454
I'm known to locate certain things
from time to time.

306
00:25:40,664 --> 00:25:43,249
I wonder if you might get me
a rock hammer.

307
00:25:43,959 --> 00:25:45,251
A rock hammer.

308
00:25:45,627 --> 00:25:48,295
- What is it and why?
- What do you care?

309
00:25:49,631 --> 00:25:52,341
For a toothbrush, I wouldn't ask.
I'd quote a price.

310
00:25:52,551 --> 00:25:54,969
But a toothbrush
is a non-lethal object, isn't it?

311
00:25:56,555 --> 00:25:57,972
Fair enough.

312
00:25:58,390 --> 00:26:01,016
A rock hammer is about
six or seven inches long.

313
00:26:01,226 --> 00:26:03,561
- Looks like a miniature pickax.
- Pickax?

314
00:26:03,770 --> 00:26:04,979
For rocks.

315
00:26:07,566 --> 00:26:08,816
Quartz?

316
00:26:12,737 --> 00:26:16,198
And some mica, shale...

317
00:26:17,450 --> 00:26:18,701
limestone.

318
00:26:18,952 --> 00:26:20,077
So?

319
00:26:20,996 --> 00:26:22,830
So I'm a rock hound.

320
00:26:23,290 --> 00:26:26,375
At least I was in my old life.
I'd like to be again.

321
00:26:26,668 --> 00:26:29,795
Or maybe you'd like to sink your toy
into somebody's skull.

322
00:26:31,256 --> 00:26:32,840
No, I have no enemies here.

323
00:26:33,008 --> 00:26:35,342
No? Wait a while.

324
00:26:36,970 --> 00:26:38,554
Word gets around.

325
00:26:39,222 --> 00:26:41,724
The Sisters have taken
quite a liking to you.

326
00:26:43,101 --> 00:26:44,893
Especially Bogs.

327
00:26:45,895 --> 00:26:49,356
Don't suppose it would help if I
told them I'm not homosexual.

328
00:26:49,524 --> 00:26:50,983
Neither are they.

329
00:26:51,192 --> 00:26:54,653
You have to be human first.
They don't qualify.

330
00:26:59,159 --> 00:27:03,537
Bull queers take by force.
That's all they want or understand.

331
00:27:03,747 --> 00:27:07,291
If I were you, I'd grow eyes
in the back of my head.

332
00:27:07,500 --> 00:27:10,252
- Thanks for the advice.
- Well, that's free.

333
00:27:10,587 --> 00:27:12,546
You understand my concern.

334
00:27:12,756 --> 00:27:15,382
If there's trouble,
I won't use the rock hammer.

335
00:27:16,259 --> 00:27:20,346
Then I'd guess you want to escape.
Tunnel under the wall, maybe.

336
00:27:21,222 --> 00:27:22,890
What did I miss? What's so funny?

337
00:27:23,308 --> 00:27:26,018
You'll understand
when you see the rock hammer.

338
00:27:27,854 --> 00:27:30,064
What's an item like this usually go for?

339
00:27:30,273 --> 00:27:32,775
Seven dollars in any rock-and-gem shop.

340
00:27:33,276 --> 00:27:35,736
My normal markup's 20 percent.

341
00:27:35,945 --> 00:27:38,322
But this is a specialty item.

342
00:27:38,531 --> 00:27:42,993
Risk goes up, price goes up.
Let's make it an even 10 bucks.

343
00:27:43,203 --> 00:27:44,536
Ten it is.

344
00:27:46,247 --> 00:27:48,290
Waste of money, if you ask me.

345
00:27:48,583 --> 00:27:49,875
Why's that?

346
00:27:51,252 --> 00:27:54,296
Folks around this joint
love surprise inspections.

347
00:27:55,924 --> 00:27:57,883
They find it, you're going to lose it.

348
00:27:58,093 --> 00:28:00,177
If they catch you, you don't know me.

349
00:28:00,387 --> 00:28:02,596
Mention my name,
we never do business again.

350
00:28:03,098 --> 00:28:06,225
Not for shoelaces or a stick of gum.
Now you got that?

351
00:28:07,060 --> 00:28:08,602
I understand.

352
00:28:09,813 --> 00:28:13,148
Thank you, Mr... Red.

353
00:28:13,900 --> 00:28:15,192
Name's Red.

354
00:28:16,611 --> 00:28:18,278
Why do they call you that?

355
00:28:22,033 --> 00:28:24,034
Maybe it's because I'm lrish.

356
00:28:32,210 --> 00:28:35,087
I could see why some of the boys
took him for snobby.

357
00:28:35,964 --> 00:28:38,382
He had a quiet way about him...

358
00:28:38,717 --> 00:28:42,886
a walk and a talk that just
wasn't normal around here.

359
00:28:43,221 --> 00:28:44,680
He strolled...

360
00:28:44,889 --> 00:28:49,101
like a man in the park without a care
or a worry in the world.

361
00:28:49,310 --> 00:28:53,981
Like he had on an invisible coat
that would shield him from this place.

362
00:28:55,900 --> 00:28:58,152
I think it would be fair to say...

363
00:28:58,403 --> 00:29:00,654
I liked Andy from the start.

364
00:29:02,407 --> 00:29:05,993
Let's go! Some of us
got a schedule to keep.

365
00:29:09,330 --> 00:29:11,832
Move it! Come on, move it!

366
00:29:14,419 --> 00:29:17,337
How you doing?
How's the wife treating you?

367
00:29:29,017 --> 00:29:30,976
Keep it moving.

368
00:29:34,272 --> 00:29:36,023
Red.

369
00:29:55,502 --> 00:29:56,960
Andy was right.

370
00:29:57,212 --> 00:29:59,421
I finally got the joke.

371
00:29:59,714 --> 00:30:02,132
It would take a man about 600 years...

372
00:30:02,342 --> 00:30:04,802
to tunnel under the wall
with one of these.

373
00:30:08,556 --> 00:30:11,016
- Book?
- Not today.

374
00:30:17,065 --> 00:30:19,066
- Book?
- No.

375
00:30:25,406 --> 00:30:27,574
Delivery for Dufresne.

376
00:30:38,378 --> 00:30:39,878
Book?

377
00:30:43,049 --> 00:30:46,844
Dufresne, here's your book.

378
00:30:51,850 --> 00:30:53,100
Thanks.

379
00:30:59,357 --> 00:31:03,068
We're running low on hexite.
Get on back and fetch us up some.

380
00:31:40,356 --> 00:31:41,940
This will blind you.

381
00:31:42,317 --> 00:31:44,693
Honey, hush.

382
00:31:57,248 --> 00:31:59,207
That's it. You fight!

383
00:31:59,417 --> 00:32:00,876
Better that way.

384
00:32:09,135 --> 00:32:12,220
I wish I could tell you
Andy fought the good fight...

385
00:32:12,430 --> 00:32:14,431
and the Sisters let him be.

386
00:32:15,016 --> 00:32:16,850
I wish I could tell you that...

387
00:32:17,018 --> 00:32:20,020
but prison is no fairy-tale world.

388
00:32:21,147 --> 00:32:23,106
He never said who did it.

389
00:32:23,358 --> 00:32:24,942
But we all knew.

390
00:32:29,781 --> 00:32:32,282
Things went on like that for a while.

391
00:32:32,700 --> 00:32:35,202
Prison life consists of routine...

392
00:32:35,453 --> 00:32:37,412
and then more routine.

393
00:32:39,916 --> 00:32:43,460
Every so often, Andy would show up
with fresh bruises.

394
00:32:44,921 --> 00:32:46,755
The Sisters kept at him.

395
00:32:47,006 --> 00:32:49,049
Sometimes he was able
to fight them off.

396
00:32:49,258 --> 00:32:50,759
Sometimes not.

397
00:32:51,928 --> 00:32:54,096
And that's how it went for Andy.

398
00:32:54,681 --> 00:32:56,431
That was his routine.

399
00:32:57,266 --> 00:33:00,727
I do believe those first two years
were the worst for him.

400
00:33:01,229 --> 00:33:04,564
And I also believe
if things had gone on that way...

401
00:33:04,899 --> 00:33:07,359
this place would have
got the best of him.

402
00:33:08,111 --> 00:33:10,904
But then, in the spring of 1949...

403
00:33:11,114 --> 00:33:13,031
the powers that be decided:

404
00:33:13,241 --> 00:33:16,576
The roof of the license-plate factory
needs resurfacing.

405
00:33:16,744 --> 00:33:19,955
I need a dozen volunteers
for a week's work.

406
00:33:20,665 --> 00:33:22,124
As you know...

407
00:33:22,875 --> 00:33:26,420
special detail carries with it
special privileges.

408
00:33:26,629 --> 00:33:29,047
It was outdoor detail...

409
00:33:29,424 --> 00:33:33,719
and May is one damned fine month
to be working outdoors.

410
00:33:34,178 --> 00:33:35,262
Stay in line there.

411
00:33:35,471 --> 00:33:38,640
More than 100 men
volunteered for the job.

412
00:33:42,937 --> 00:33:45,939
Wallace E. Unger.

413
00:33:46,441 --> 00:33:48,775
Ellis Redding.

414
00:33:48,985 --> 00:33:50,569
Wouldn't you know it?

415
00:33:50,987 --> 00:33:54,281
Me and some fellows I know
were among the names called.

416
00:33:54,490 --> 00:33:56,491
Andrew Dufresne.

417
00:33:56,909 --> 00:33:59,828
It only cost us
a pack of smokes per man.

418
00:34:00,329 --> 00:34:02,789
I made my usual 20 percent, of course.

419
00:34:02,999 --> 00:34:06,460
So this big-shot lawyer
calls me long-distance from Texas.

420
00:34:06,669 --> 00:34:08,253
I say, "Yeah?"

421
00:34:08,504 --> 00:34:12,132
He says, "Sorry to inform you,
but your brother just died."

422
00:34:12,341 --> 00:34:16,261
- I'm sorry to hear that.
- I'm not. He was an asshole.

423
00:34:16,471 --> 00:34:18,638
Ran off years ago.
Figured him for dead.

424
00:34:18,848 --> 00:34:21,141
So this lawyer fellow says to me:

425
00:34:21,350 --> 00:34:25,479
"He died a rich man." Oil wells and shit.
Close to a million bucks.

426
00:34:26,147 --> 00:34:28,023
A million bucks?

427
00:34:28,316 --> 00:34:32,819
- Incredible how lucky some assholes get.
- You going to see any of that?

428
00:34:33,446 --> 00:34:36,198
Thirty-five thousand.
That's what he left me.

429
00:34:36,407 --> 00:34:38,158
- Dollars?
- Yep.

430
00:34:38,326 --> 00:34:41,328
That's great!
That's like winning the sweepstakes.

431
00:34:41,662 --> 00:34:42,829
Isn't it?

432
00:34:42,997 --> 00:34:45,957
Dumb shit, what do you think
the government will do to me?

433
00:34:46,167 --> 00:34:48,502
Take a big wet bite
out of my ass is what.

434
00:34:49,295 --> 00:34:50,629
Poor Byron.

435
00:34:51,506 --> 00:34:54,674
Terrible fucking luck, huh?
Crying shame.

436
00:34:54,884 --> 00:34:57,177
Some people really got it awful.

437
00:34:57,428 --> 00:34:58,804
Andy, are you nuts?

438
00:34:59,013 --> 00:35:00,889
Keep your eyes on your mop, man!

439
00:35:01,099 --> 00:35:04,059
You'll pay some tax,
but you'll still end up...

440
00:35:04,268 --> 00:35:07,062
Yeah, maybe enough to buy
a new car, and then what?

441
00:35:07,271 --> 00:35:09,439
I got to pay tax on the car. Repair...

442
00:35:09,690 --> 00:35:13,401
maintenance, kids pestering you
to take them for a ride all the time.

443
00:35:13,653 --> 00:35:17,322
Then if you figure your tax wrong,
you pay out of your own pocket.

444
00:35:17,532 --> 00:35:19,658
I tell you! Uncle Sam!

445
00:35:19,867 --> 00:35:23,870
He puts his hand in your shirt
and squeezes your tit till it's purple.

446
00:35:26,541 --> 00:35:28,708
- Getting himself killed.
- Keep tarring.

447
00:35:28,918 --> 00:35:31,461
Some brother. Shit!

448
00:35:36,384 --> 00:35:37,801
Mr. Hadley...

449
00:35:38,678 --> 00:35:40,053
do you trust your wife?

450
00:35:41,681 --> 00:35:43,140
Oh, that's funny.

451
00:35:43,683 --> 00:35:46,351
You'll look funnier
sucking my dick with no teeth.

452
00:35:46,519 --> 00:35:49,855
What I mean is, do you think
she'd go behind your back?

453
00:35:50,982 --> 00:35:54,401
Step aside, Mert. This fucker's
having himself an accident.

454
00:35:54,569 --> 00:35:55,694
He'll push him off!

455
00:35:55,862 --> 00:35:57,737
If you trust her, you can keep...

456
00:35:57,905 --> 00:35:59,322
that 35,000.

457
00:36:00,074 --> 00:36:03,243
- What did you say?
- Thirty-five thousand.

458
00:36:03,411 --> 00:36:04,411
All of it.

459
00:36:04,620 --> 00:36:07,706
- Every penny.
- You better start making sense.

460
00:36:07,915 --> 00:36:10,250
If you want to keep it,
give it to your wife.

461
00:36:10,418 --> 00:36:14,337
The IRS allows a one-time-only gift
to your spouse for up to $60,000.

462
00:36:14,547 --> 00:36:16,923
- Bullshit. Tax-free?
- Tax-free.

463
00:36:17,091 --> 00:36:19,092
IRS can't touch one cent.

464
00:36:19,468 --> 00:36:21,928
You're that smart banker
what killed his wife.

465
00:36:22,180 --> 00:36:25,557
Why should I believe you?
So I can end up in here with you?

466
00:36:25,766 --> 00:36:28,602
It's legal. Ask the IRS.
They'll say the same thing.

467
00:36:28,769 --> 00:36:32,856
I feel stupid telling you this.
I'm sure you would have investigated.

468
00:36:33,065 --> 00:36:36,735
I don't need you to tell me
where the bear shit in the buckwheat.

469
00:36:36,944 --> 00:36:40,322
Of course not. But you do need
someone to set it up for you.

470
00:36:40,531 --> 00:36:42,115
That'll cost you. A lawyer.

471
00:36:42,283 --> 00:36:44,576
A bunch of ball-washing bastards!

472
00:36:45,036 --> 00:36:48,496
I suppose I could set it up for you.
That would save you some money.

473
00:36:48,706 --> 00:36:50,790
You get the forms, I'll prepare them...

474
00:36:51,000 --> 00:36:52,751
nearly free of charge.

475
00:36:53,961 --> 00:36:57,297
I'd only ask three beers apiece
for each of my coworkers.

476
00:36:58,257 --> 00:36:59,799
"Coworkers." That's rich!

477
00:37:00,635 --> 00:37:03,136
A man working outdoors
feels more like a man...

478
00:37:03,346 --> 00:37:06,806
if he can have a bottle of suds.
That's only my opinion...

479
00:37:07,266 --> 00:37:08,266
sir.

480
00:37:12,188 --> 00:37:14,147
What are you jimmies staring at?

481
00:37:14,315 --> 00:37:15,941
Let's go! Work!

482
00:37:25,451 --> 00:37:27,369
And that's how it came to pass...

483
00:37:27,578 --> 00:37:30,247
that on the second-to-last
day of the job...

484
00:37:30,456 --> 00:37:35,001
the convict crew that tarred
the factory roof in the spring of '49...

485
00:37:35,211 --> 00:37:38,338
wound up sitting in a row
at 10:00 in the morning...

486
00:37:38,547 --> 00:37:44,010
drinking icy-cold beer,
courtesy of the hardest screw...

487
00:37:44,220 --> 00:37:47,514
that ever walked a turn
at Shawshank State Prison.

488
00:37:47,682 --> 00:37:50,141
Drink up while it's cold, ladies.

489
00:37:51,227 --> 00:37:55,814
The colossal prick even managed
to sound magnanimous.

490
00:37:56,941 --> 00:38:01,403
We sat and drank with the sun
on our shoulders and felt like free men.

491
00:38:01,779 --> 00:38:05,198
We could have been tarring
the roof of one of our own houses.

492
00:38:05,408 --> 00:38:08,243
We were the lords of all creation.

493
00:38:08,828 --> 00:38:10,412
As for Andy...

494
00:38:10,663 --> 00:38:13,290
he spent that break
hunkered in the shade...

495
00:38:13,499 --> 00:38:16,001
a strange little smile on his face...

496
00:38:16,210 --> 00:38:18,420
watching us drink his beer.

497
00:38:26,554 --> 00:38:27,887
Want a cold one?

498
00:38:28,556 --> 00:38:31,516
No, thanks. I gave up drinking.

499
00:38:35,479 --> 00:38:38,565
You could argue he'd done it
to curry favor with the guards.

500
00:38:39,233 --> 00:38:43,069
Or maybe make a few friends
among us cons.

501
00:38:43,779 --> 00:38:44,863
Me?

502
00:38:45,072 --> 00:38:47,866
I think he did it
just to feel normal again...

503
00:38:48,284 --> 00:38:50,535
if only for a short while.

504
00:38:53,164 --> 00:38:54,247
King me.

505
00:38:56,125 --> 00:38:58,752
- Chess. Now there's a game of kings.
- What?

506
00:38:58,961 --> 00:39:00,712
Civilized. Strategic.

507
00:39:01,380 --> 00:39:04,382
And a total fucking mystery. I hate it.

508
00:39:04,633 --> 00:39:06,426
Let me teach you someday.

509
00:39:07,928 --> 00:39:08,928
Sure.

510
00:39:09,430 --> 00:39:11,139
We could get a board together.

511
00:39:11,390 --> 00:39:14,434
You're talking to the right man.
I can get things, right?

512
00:39:14,643 --> 00:39:18,646
We might do business on a board,
and I'll carve the pieces myself.

513
00:39:18,856 --> 00:39:22,150
One side in alabaster, one in soapstone.
What do you think?

514
00:39:22,777 --> 00:39:24,152
I think it'll take years.

515
00:39:24,362 --> 00:39:26,905
Years I got.
What I don't have are the rocks.

516
00:39:27,114 --> 00:39:29,074
Pickings are pretty slim in the yard.

517
00:39:29,283 --> 00:39:31,117
Pebbles, mostly.

518
00:39:35,456 --> 00:39:38,249
We're getting to be
kind of friends, aren't we?

519
00:39:39,126 --> 00:39:40,668
Yeah, I guess.

520
00:39:41,295 --> 00:39:42,837
Can I ask you something?

521
00:39:44,298 --> 00:39:45,757
Why'd you do it?

522
00:39:46,967 --> 00:39:48,551
I'm innocent, Red.

523
00:39:48,761 --> 00:39:50,804
Just like everybody else here.

524
00:39:55,142 --> 00:39:56,684
What are you in for?

525
00:39:59,397 --> 00:40:01,564
Murder. Same as you.

526
00:40:01,774 --> 00:40:02,941
Innocent?

527
00:40:05,653 --> 00:40:08,029
Only guilty man in Shawshank.

528
00:41:07,631 --> 00:41:08,882
Where's the canary?

529
00:41:09,049 --> 00:41:10,383
How did you know?

530
00:41:10,551 --> 00:41:12,886
- How did I know what?
- So you don't know.

531
00:41:13,053 --> 00:41:14,220
Come.

532
00:41:16,724 --> 00:41:18,850
This is where the canary is.

533
00:41:21,520 --> 00:41:24,856
Quite a surprise to hear
a woman singing in my house, eh?

534
00:41:28,360 --> 00:41:29,736
That's quite a...

535
00:41:30,696 --> 00:41:32,363
surprise.

536
00:41:36,660 --> 00:41:38,077
Wait, wait.

537
00:41:38,579 --> 00:41:40,079
Here she comes.

538
00:41:40,372 --> 00:41:43,249
I like this part when she
does that shit with her hair.

539
00:41:43,417 --> 00:41:46,169
I know. I've seen it
three times this month.

540
00:41:46,378 --> 00:41:48,254
Gilda, are you decent?

541
00:41:49,256 --> 00:41:50,423
Me?

542
00:41:53,093 --> 00:41:54,886
God, I love it.

543
00:42:00,059 --> 00:42:03,061
I understand you're a man
that knows how to get things.

544
00:42:04,063 --> 00:42:07,774
I'm known to locate certain things
from time to time. What do you want?

545
00:42:07,983 --> 00:42:10,109
- Rita Hayworth.
- What?

546
00:42:10,694 --> 00:42:12,070
Can you get her?

547
00:42:13,447 --> 00:42:16,824
So this is Johnny Farrel.
I've heard a lot about you.

548
00:42:18,077 --> 00:42:20,370
- Take a few weeks.
- Weeks?

549
00:42:20,579 --> 00:42:24,958
I don't have her stuffed down the front
of my pants right now, sorry to say.

550
00:42:25,543 --> 00:42:26,876
But I'll get her.

551
00:42:27,086 --> 00:42:28,419
Relax.

552
00:42:30,297 --> 00:42:31,589
Thanks.

553
00:42:51,986 --> 00:42:53,945
- Take a walk!
- I got to change reels!

554
00:42:54,154 --> 00:42:56,155
I said fuck off!

555
00:43:02,329 --> 00:43:03,663
Ain't you going to scream?

556
00:43:04,999 --> 00:43:06,874
Let's get this over with.

557
00:43:12,006 --> 00:43:14,007
He broke my fucking nose!

558
00:43:23,309 --> 00:43:24,517
Now...

559
00:43:25,019 --> 00:43:27,186
I'm going to open my fly...

560
00:43:27,438 --> 00:43:30,189
and you'll swallow
what I give you to swallow.

561
00:43:31,358 --> 00:43:33,943
Then you'll swallow Rooster's.
You broke his nose.

562
00:43:34,153 --> 00:43:36,279
He ought to have
something to show for it.

563
00:43:36,488 --> 00:43:38,364
You put it in my mouth,
you lose it.

564
00:43:38,532 --> 00:43:41,159
No, you don't understand.

565
00:43:41,493 --> 00:43:44,537
Do that and I'll put all eight inches
of this in your ear.

566
00:43:44,705 --> 00:43:48,207
All right, but you should know
that sudden, serious brain injury...

567
00:43:48,375 --> 00:43:50,335
causes the victim to bite down hard.

568
00:43:51,795 --> 00:43:54,047
In fact, I hear the bite reflex
is so strong...

569
00:43:54,840 --> 00:43:57,300
they have to pry
the victim's jaws open...

570
00:43:57,509 --> 00:43:58,885
with a crowbar.

571
00:44:01,847 --> 00:44:03,389
Where do you get this shit?

572
00:44:03,557 --> 00:44:04,974
I read it.

573
00:44:06,393 --> 00:44:09,062
You know how to read,
you ignorant fuck?

574
00:44:10,731 --> 00:44:12,023
Honey.

575
00:44:13,734 --> 00:44:15,485
You shouldn't!

576
00:44:18,155 --> 00:44:21,074
Bogs didn't put anything
in Andy's mouth.

577
00:44:21,325 --> 00:44:23,409
And neither did his friends.

578
00:44:23,827 --> 00:44:27,664
What they did do is beat him
within an inch of his life.

579
00:44:28,332 --> 00:44:30,833
Andy spent a month in the infirmary.

580
00:44:31,627 --> 00:44:34,170
Bogs spent a week in the hole.

581
00:44:38,258 --> 00:44:39,759
Time's up, Bogs.

582
00:44:43,597 --> 00:44:45,264
It's your world, boss.

583
00:44:48,519 --> 00:44:51,312
Return to your cellblocks
for evening count.

584
00:44:51,522 --> 00:44:54,190
All prisoners report for lockdown.

585
00:45:09,123 --> 00:45:10,123
What?

586
00:45:22,803 --> 00:45:25,304
- Where's he going?
- Grab his ankles.

587
00:45:28,642 --> 00:45:32,395
No! No! Help me!

588
00:45:36,066 --> 00:45:38,651
Two things never happened again
after that.

589
00:45:38,944 --> 00:45:42,071
The Sisters never
laid a finger on Andy again.

590
00:45:42,906 --> 00:45:45,408
And Bogs never walked again.

591
00:45:46,577 --> 00:45:50,079
They transferred him
to a minimum-security hospital upstate.

592
00:45:50,289 --> 00:45:52,790
To my knowledge,
he lived out the rest of his days...

593
00:45:52,958 --> 00:45:55,084
drinking his food through a straw.

594
00:45:56,086 --> 00:46:00,173
Andy could use a nice "welcome back"
when he gets out of the infirmary.

595
00:46:01,925 --> 00:46:03,509
Sounds good to us.

596
00:46:03,761 --> 00:46:06,262
I figure we owe him that much
for the beer.

597
00:46:07,014 --> 00:46:09,265
The man likes to play chess.

598
00:46:09,767 --> 00:46:11,684
Let's get him some rocks.

599
00:46:44,301 --> 00:46:45,551
Guys!

600
00:46:46,303 --> 00:46:47,386
I got one.

601
00:46:47,554 --> 00:46:49,055
I got one. Look!

602
00:46:50,974 --> 00:46:55,061
Heywood, that isn't soapstone!
And it ain't alabaster either.

603
00:46:55,229 --> 00:46:57,146
What are you, a fucking geologist?

604
00:46:57,356 --> 00:46:59,065
He's right. It ain't.

605
00:46:59,274 --> 00:47:02,193
- What the hell is it then?
- It's a horse apple.

606
00:47:03,153 --> 00:47:05,571
- Bullshit!
- No, horseshit.

607
00:47:05,739 --> 00:47:07,240
Petrified.

608
00:47:12,746 --> 00:47:14,747
Oh, Jesus.

609
00:47:16,250 --> 00:47:17,416
Damn!

610
00:47:17,751 --> 00:47:21,963
Despite a few hitches,
the boys came through in fine style.

611
00:47:22,172 --> 00:47:24,173
And by the weekend
he was due back...

612
00:47:24,383 --> 00:47:28,094
we had enough rocks saved up
to keep him busy till rapture.

613
00:47:28,929 --> 00:47:31,430
Also got a big shipment in that week.

614
00:47:31,682 --> 00:47:34,058
Cigarettes... chewing gum...

615
00:47:34,268 --> 00:47:35,726
sipping whisky...

616
00:47:35,936 --> 00:47:39,313
playing cards with naked ladies
on them. You name it.

617
00:47:39,523 --> 00:47:42,275
And, of course, the most important item:

618
00:47:44,111 --> 00:47:46,195
Rita Hayworth herself.

619
00:48:20,355 --> 00:48:23,107
- Okay, look alive!
- Open all tiers.

620
00:48:23,317 --> 00:48:25,568
Heads up. They're tossing cells.

621
00:48:25,777 --> 00:48:28,487
Heads up. They're tossing cells!

622
00:48:30,073 --> 00:48:31,574
119.

623
00:48:33,410 --> 00:48:35,077
123.

624
00:48:45,339 --> 00:48:46,339
On your feet.

625
00:48:49,009 --> 00:48:50,509
Face the wall.

626
00:49:24,628 --> 00:49:26,545
Turn around and face the warden.

627
00:49:33,136 --> 00:49:35,221
Pleased to see you reading this.

628
00:49:36,556 --> 00:49:38,474
Any favorite passages?

629
00:49:39,351 --> 00:49:41,727
"Watch ye, therefore,
for ye know not...

630
00:49:41,895 --> 00:49:44,146
when the master
of the house cometh."

631
00:49:45,273 --> 00:49:47,441
Mark 13:35.

632
00:49:48,193 --> 00:49:50,069
I've always liked that one.

633
00:49:50,988 --> 00:49:52,655
But I prefer:

634
00:49:53,115 --> 00:49:54,991
"I am the light of the world.

635
00:49:55,450 --> 00:49:58,744
Ye that followeth me
shall have the light of life."

636
00:49:58,954 --> 00:50:01,580
John, chapter 8, verse 12.

637
00:50:01,873 --> 00:50:03,916
I hear you're good with numbers.

638
00:50:04,084 --> 00:50:05,084
How nice.

639
00:50:06,336 --> 00:50:08,254
Man should have a skill.

640
00:50:10,799 --> 00:50:11,841
Explain this.

641
00:50:13,010 --> 00:50:17,096
It's called a rock blanket.
For shaping and polishing rocks.

642
00:50:17,514 --> 00:50:19,432
A little hobby of mine.

643
00:50:30,277 --> 00:50:31,736
It's pretty clean.

644
00:50:31,987 --> 00:50:35,114
Some contraband here,
but nothing to get in a twist over.

645
00:50:39,453 --> 00:50:41,454
I can't say I approve of this.

646
00:50:43,081 --> 00:50:44,540
But I suppose...

647
00:50:46,626 --> 00:50:48,627
exceptions can be made.

648
00:50:58,972 --> 00:51:00,306
Lock them up!

649
00:51:03,226 --> 00:51:04,810
I almost forgot.

650
00:51:05,228 --> 00:51:07,396
I'd hate to deprive you of this.

651
00:51:08,148 --> 00:51:10,066
Salvation lies within.

652
00:51:10,275 --> 00:51:11,317
Yes, sir.

653
00:51:19,868 --> 00:51:22,453
Tossing cells was just an excuse.

654
00:51:22,913 --> 00:51:26,832
Truth is... Norton
wanted to size Andy up.

655
00:51:40,514 --> 00:51:42,848
My wife made that in church group.

656
00:51:45,519 --> 00:51:46,811
Very nice, sir.

657
00:51:48,355 --> 00:51:49,855
You enjoy working the laundry?

658
00:51:51,525 --> 00:51:53,192
No, sir. Not especially.

659
00:51:53,527 --> 00:51:55,986
Perhaps we can find something more...

660
00:51:56,238 --> 00:51:58,697
befitting a man of your education.

661
00:52:06,748 --> 00:52:08,249
Hey, Jake. Where's Brooks?

662
00:52:10,085 --> 00:52:12,878
I thought I heard you out here.

663
00:52:13,547 --> 00:52:15,089
I've been reassigned to you.

664
00:52:15,382 --> 00:52:17,716
I know, they told me.

665
00:52:18,552 --> 00:52:20,594
Ain't that a kick in the head?

666
00:52:20,804 --> 00:52:23,097
Well, I'll give you the dime tour.

667
00:52:23,306 --> 00:52:24,473
Come on.

668
00:52:25,892 --> 00:52:27,601
Well, here she is.

669
00:52:27,811 --> 00:52:29,812
The Shawshank Prison Library.

670
00:52:30,480 --> 00:52:32,481
National Geographics...

671
00:52:33,400 --> 00:52:36,193
Reader's Digest condensed books...

672
00:52:36,403 --> 00:52:37,987
and Louis L'Amour.

673
00:52:38,572 --> 00:52:40,406
Look magazine.

674
00:52:40,740 --> 00:52:43,075
Erle Stanley Gardners.

675
00:52:43,326 --> 00:52:46,787
Every evening I load up the cart
and make my rounds.

676
00:52:46,997 --> 00:52:49,665
I enter the names
on this clipboard here.

677
00:52:50,167 --> 00:52:52,918
Easy, peasy, Japanese-y.

678
00:52:53,628 --> 00:52:56,547
- Any questions?
- How long have you been librarian?

679
00:52:57,757 --> 00:53:01,760
I come here in '05,
and they made me librarian in 1912.

680
00:53:03,096 --> 00:53:05,264
And have you ever had an assistant?

681
00:53:05,432 --> 00:53:07,933
No. Not much to it, really.

682
00:53:08,685 --> 00:53:09,935
Why me? Why now?

683
00:53:10,353 --> 00:53:11,645
I don't know.

684
00:53:11,855 --> 00:53:14,899
But it'd be nice to have
some company down here.

685
00:53:26,119 --> 00:53:28,454
That's him. That's the one.

686
00:53:36,087 --> 00:53:37,254
I'm Dekins.

687
00:53:37,631 --> 00:53:39,298
I was...

688
00:53:39,966 --> 00:53:43,802
thinking about setting up some kind of
trust fund for my kids' educations.

689
00:53:47,724 --> 00:53:49,183
I see.

690
00:53:54,314 --> 00:53:57,274
Why don't we have a seat
and talk it over.

691
00:54:00,487 --> 00:54:03,447
Do you have a piece of paper
and a pencil?

692
00:54:14,793 --> 00:54:16,085
Thanks.

693
00:54:16,753 --> 00:54:17,836
So...

694
00:54:19,589 --> 00:54:21,340
Mr. Dekins...

695
00:54:22,175 --> 00:54:24,260
And then Andy says, "Mr. Dekins..."

696
00:54:24,469 --> 00:54:27,471
do you want your sons
to go to Harvard or Yale?"

697
00:54:27,681 --> 00:54:28,722
He didn't say that!

698
00:54:29,057 --> 00:54:31,558
As God as my witness!

699
00:54:31,851 --> 00:54:33,560
Dekins blinked for a second...

700
00:54:33,770 --> 00:54:36,897
then he laughed
and actually shook Andy's hand.

701
00:54:37,357 --> 00:54:39,692
- My ass!
- Shook his hand.

702
00:54:39,859 --> 00:54:42,736
I tell you, I near soiled myself!

703
00:54:42,946 --> 00:54:47,199
All he needed was a suit and tie
and a jiggly hula gal on his desk...

704
00:54:47,409 --> 00:54:50,035
he'd have been
"Mr. Dufresne," if you please.

705
00:54:50,203 --> 00:54:51,870
Making a few friends?

706
00:54:53,164 --> 00:54:54,832
I wouldn't say "friends."

707
00:54:55,041 --> 00:54:58,877
I'm a convicted murderer
who provides sound financial planning.

708
00:54:59,045 --> 00:55:01,380
It's a wonderful pet to have.

709
00:55:01,589 --> 00:55:03,382
Got you out of the laundry, though.

710
00:55:03,925 --> 00:55:05,843
It might do more than that.

711
00:55:06,052 --> 00:55:08,762
How about expanding the library.
Get some new books.

712
00:55:08,972 --> 00:55:11,557
If you ask for something,
ask for a pool table.

713
00:55:13,268 --> 00:55:16,270
How do you expect to do that? I mean...

714
00:55:16,479 --> 00:55:19,440
get new books in here,
"Mr. Dufresne, if you please."

715
00:55:19,899 --> 00:55:21,984
I'll ask the warden for funds.

716
00:55:22,861 --> 00:55:27,114
Six wardens have been through here
in my tenure, and I've learned...

717
00:55:27,365 --> 00:55:29,742
one immutable, universal truth:

718
00:55:29,909 --> 00:55:32,202
Not one of them born whose asshole...

719
00:55:32,370 --> 00:55:36,415
wouldn't pucker up tighter than
a snare drum when you ask for funds.

720
00:55:37,292 --> 00:55:40,210
- The budget's stretched thin as it is.
- I see.

721
00:55:40,420 --> 00:55:43,839
Perhaps I could write the state senate
and request funds from them.

722
00:55:44,049 --> 00:55:48,135
They have only three ways to spend
the taxpayers' money for prisons:

723
00:55:48,345 --> 00:55:50,763
More walls, more bars, more guards.

724
00:55:50,972 --> 00:55:53,640
I'd like to try, with permission.
A letter a week.

725
00:55:53,850 --> 00:55:56,602
- They can't ignore me forever.
- Sure can.

726
00:55:56,853 --> 00:55:59,521
But you write your letters
if it makes you happy.

727
00:55:59,814 --> 00:56:02,441
I'll even mail them for you. How's that?

728
00:56:04,110 --> 00:56:06,904
So Andy started writing
a letter a week...

729
00:56:07,113 --> 00:56:08,697
just like he said.

730
00:56:12,869 --> 00:56:15,496
And, just like Norton said...

731
00:56:15,705 --> 00:56:17,164
Andy got no answers.

732
00:56:25,382 --> 00:56:30,302
The following April, Andy did tax returns
for half the guards at Shawshank.

733
00:56:31,638 --> 00:56:33,889
Year after that, he did them all...

734
00:56:34,140 --> 00:56:36,058
including the warden's.

735
00:56:37,811 --> 00:56:41,271
Year after that,
they rescheduled the intramural season...

736
00:56:41,481 --> 00:56:43,899
to coincide with tax season.

737
00:56:45,485 --> 00:56:49,947
The guards on the opposing teams
all remembered to bring their W-2s.

738
00:56:50,156 --> 00:56:51,490
So Moresby Prison...

739
00:56:51,658 --> 00:56:53,951
issued you a gun,
but you paid for it.

740
00:56:54,160 --> 00:56:55,869
Right. The holster too.

741
00:56:56,079 --> 00:56:58,539
That's tax-deductible.
You can write that off.

742
00:56:58,748 --> 00:57:01,792
Yes, sir.
Andy was a regular cottage industry.

743
00:57:02,502 --> 00:57:07,005
In fact, it got so busy at tax time,
he was allowed a staff.

744
00:57:07,257 --> 00:57:09,716
Could you hand me
a stack of 1040s?

745
00:57:09,926 --> 00:57:14,763
Got me out of the wood shop a month out
of the year, and that was fine by me.

746
00:57:16,015 --> 00:57:19,184
And still, he kept sending those letters.

747
00:57:25,942 --> 00:57:26,984
It's Brooks.

748
00:57:28,111 --> 00:57:29,611
Watch the door.

749
00:57:29,863 --> 00:57:31,196
Please, Brooks.

750
00:57:31,364 --> 00:57:33,240
- Calm the fuck down.
- Stay back!

751
00:57:33,700 --> 00:57:36,326
- Stay back, goddamn it!
- What's going on?

752
00:57:36,536 --> 00:57:39,079
One second he's fine,
then out come the knife.

753
00:57:39,289 --> 00:57:41,081
We can talk about this, right?

754
00:57:41,374 --> 00:57:45,085
There's nothing to talk about.
I'll cut his fucking throat.

755
00:57:45,378 --> 00:57:47,087
What's he done to you?

756
00:57:47,297 --> 00:57:48,964
It's what they done!

757
00:57:49,466 --> 00:57:50,716
I got no choice.

758
00:57:51,217 --> 00:57:53,510
You won't hurt Heywood.
We all know that.

759
00:57:53,720 --> 00:57:56,180
- Right, Heywood?
- Sure. I know that.

760
00:57:56,389 --> 00:57:59,725
He's a friend of yours,
and Brooks is a reasonable man.

761
00:57:59,893 --> 00:58:01,101
Right, guys?

762
00:58:02,061 --> 00:58:04,563
So put the knife down.
Brooks, look at me.

763
00:58:04,731 --> 00:58:07,065
Put the knife down.

764
00:58:08,985 --> 00:58:11,069
Look at his neck, for God's sake.

765
00:58:11,821 --> 00:58:14,156
Look at his neck. He's bleeding.

766
00:58:15,074 --> 00:58:16,533
It's the only...

767
00:58:16,743 --> 00:58:18,785
It's the only way they'd let me stay.

768
00:58:19,078 --> 00:58:21,413
This is crazy.
You don't want to do this.

769
00:58:21,664 --> 00:58:23,749
Put it... Put it down.

770
00:58:32,509 --> 00:58:34,009
Take it easy.

771
00:58:34,677 --> 00:58:36,261
You'll be all right.

772
00:58:36,429 --> 00:58:38,889
Him? What about me?

773
00:58:39,098 --> 00:58:41,475
Crazy old fool damn near cut my throat!

774
00:58:41,684 --> 00:58:43,602
You've had worse from shaving.

775
00:58:43,770 --> 00:58:45,896
What did you do to set him off?

776
00:58:46,105 --> 00:58:48,315
Nothing. I come in here to say farewell.

777
00:58:48,942 --> 00:58:51,610
Ain't you heard?
His parole's come through.

778
00:58:53,780 --> 00:58:56,740
I just don't understand
what happened in there, that's all.

779
00:58:56,908 --> 00:58:59,743
Old man's crazy as a rat
in a tin shithouse.

780
00:58:59,953 --> 00:59:01,828
That's enough out of you.

781
00:59:02,038 --> 00:59:04,790
- Heard he had you shitting your pants.
- Fuck you.

782
00:59:05,041 --> 00:59:06,250
Knock it off.

783
00:59:07,210 --> 00:59:08,627
Brooks ain't no bug.

784
00:59:12,465 --> 00:59:14,258
He's just institutionalized.

785
00:59:15,635 --> 00:59:17,553
"Institutionalized," my ass.

786
00:59:17,762 --> 00:59:21,765
The man's been in here 50 years,
Heywood, 50 years!

787
00:59:21,975 --> 00:59:23,684
This is all he knows.

788
00:59:23,893 --> 00:59:26,186
In here, he's an important man...

789
00:59:26,396 --> 00:59:27,479
an educated man.

790
00:59:28,314 --> 00:59:30,232
Outside, he's nothing.

791
00:59:31,109 --> 00:59:34,611
Just a used-up con
with arthritis in both hands.

792
00:59:34,821 --> 00:59:37,823
Probably couldn't get a library card
if he tried.

793
00:59:38,074 --> 00:59:39,825
You know what I'm trying to say?

794
00:59:40,076 --> 00:59:42,995
I do believe
you're talking out of your ass.

795
00:59:44,247 --> 00:59:46,498
You believe whatever you want.

796
00:59:47,083 --> 00:59:49,501
But I tell you these walls are funny.

797
00:59:51,087 --> 00:59:52,754
First you hate them.

798
00:59:54,591 --> 00:59:56,508
Then you get used to them.

799
00:59:58,428 --> 01:00:00,429
Enough time passes...

800
01:00:01,097 --> 01:00:03,098
you get so you depend on them.

801
01:00:04,100 --> 01:00:06,310
That's "institutionalized."

802
01:00:06,519 --> 01:00:07,811
Shit.

803
01:00:08,021 --> 01:00:10,772
- I could never get like that.
- Oh, yeah?

804
01:00:11,649 --> 01:00:14,151
Wait till you've been here
as long as Brooks.

805
01:00:14,360 --> 01:00:15,944
Goddamn right.

806
01:00:18,531 --> 01:00:20,449
They send you here for life...

807
01:00:21,117 --> 01:00:23,452
that's exactly what they take.

808
01:00:25,204 --> 01:00:27,205
Part that counts, anyway.

809
01:00:34,797 --> 01:00:37,716
I can't take care of you no more, Jake.

810
01:00:38,885 --> 01:00:40,552
You go on now.

811
01:00:41,804 --> 01:00:46,141
You're free.

812
01:01:05,161 --> 01:01:06,828
Good luck, Brooksie.

813
01:01:09,123 --> 01:01:11,208
Take care of yourself, Brooks.

814
01:01:44,784 --> 01:01:46,284
Dear fellas:

815
01:01:46,577 --> 01:01:50,789
I can't believe how fast things move
on the outside.

816
01:01:52,083 --> 01:01:54,751
Watch it, old-timer! Want to get killed?

817
01:01:55,962 --> 01:01:59,464
I saw an automobile once
when I was a kid...

818
01:02:00,133 --> 01:02:02,551
but now they're everywhere.

819
01:02:06,222 --> 01:02:10,517
The world went and got itself
in a big damn hurry.

820
01:02:26,325 --> 01:02:30,120
The parole board
got me into this halfway house...

821
01:02:30,413 --> 01:02:33,457
called "The Brewer"...
and a job...

822
01:02:33,666 --> 01:02:36,626
bagging groceries at the Food-Way.

823
01:02:38,171 --> 01:02:40,589
It's hard work and I try to keep up...

824
01:02:40,798 --> 01:02:43,175
but my hands hurt most of the time.

825
01:02:43,468 --> 01:02:45,427
Make sure your man double-bags.

826
01:02:45,636 --> 01:02:47,679
Last time, the bottom near came out.

827
01:02:48,347 --> 01:02:51,266
Make sure you double-bag
like the lady says. Understand?

828
01:02:51,476 --> 01:02:52,851
Yes, sir. Surely will.

829
01:02:53,019 --> 01:02:56,563
I don't think the store manager
likes me very much.

830
01:02:59,567 --> 01:03:03,862
Sometimes after work,
I go to the park and feed the birds.

831
01:03:04,322 --> 01:03:05,822
I keep thinking...

832
01:03:06,032 --> 01:03:09,367
Jake might just show up
and say hello.

833
01:03:09,994 --> 01:03:11,995
But he never does.

834
01:03:13,206 --> 01:03:18,043
I hope, wherever he is, he's doing okay
and making new friends.

835
01:03:21,672 --> 01:03:24,382
I have trouble sleeping at night.

836
01:03:24,717 --> 01:03:27,969
I have bad dreams, like I'm falling.

837
01:03:28,221 --> 01:03:30,472
I wake up scared.

838
01:03:30,681 --> 01:03:34,893
Sometimes it takes me a while
to remember where I am.

839
01:03:36,395 --> 01:03:41,316
Maybe I should get me a gun and rob
the Food-Way so they'd send me home.

840
01:03:41,609 --> 01:03:45,946
I could shoot the manager while
I was at it. Sort of like a bonus.

841
01:03:47,615 --> 01:03:51,618
I guess I'm too old
for that sort of nonsense anymore.

842
01:03:51,869 --> 01:03:53,578
I don't like it here.

843
01:03:53,788 --> 01:03:57,791
I'm tired of being afraid all the time.
I've decided...

844
01:03:58,626 --> 01:04:00,293
not to stay.

845
01:04:11,222 --> 01:04:13,765
I doubt they'll kick up any fuss...

846
01:04:13,975 --> 01:04:17,477
not for an old crook like me.

847
01:05:19,957 --> 01:05:24,210
"I doubt they'll kick up any fuss,
not for an old crook like me."

848
01:05:25,254 --> 01:05:29,090
P.S. Tell Heywood I'm sorry
I put a knife to his throat.

849
01:05:29,300 --> 01:05:31,635
"No hard feelings. Brooks."

850
01:05:42,104 --> 01:05:44,064
He should have died in here.

851
01:05:49,612 --> 01:05:51,029
What the fuck have you done?

852
01:05:51,197 --> 01:05:53,865
It's a goddamn mess,
I'll tell you that.

853
01:05:59,413 --> 01:06:03,166
- What's all this?
- You tell me. They're addressed to you.

854
01:06:04,418 --> 01:06:05,752
Take it.

855
01:06:14,303 --> 01:06:15,804
"Dear Mr. Dufresne:"

856
01:06:16,931 --> 01:06:18,890
In response to your repeated inquiries...

857
01:06:19,100 --> 01:06:23,395
"...the state has allocated the enclosed
funds for your library project."

858
01:06:24,146 --> 01:06:25,981
This is $200.

859
01:06:26,190 --> 01:06:30,193
"In addition, the library district
has generously responded..."

860
01:06:30,403 --> 01:06:32,946
with a donation of used books
and sundries.

861
01:06:33,155 --> 01:06:37,283
We trust this will fill your needs.
We now consider the matter closed.

862
01:06:37,493 --> 01:06:39,369
"Please stop sending us letters."

863
01:06:39,537 --> 01:06:42,205
Clear all this out
before the warden gets back.

864
01:06:42,415 --> 01:06:43,581
Yes, sir.

865
01:06:47,878 --> 01:06:49,045
Good for you, Andy.

866
01:06:54,343 --> 01:06:56,261
It only took six years.

867
01:06:57,847 --> 01:07:00,598
From now on, I'll write two
letters a week instead of one.

868
01:07:00,766 --> 01:07:04,102
I believe you're crazy enough.
Get this stuff out...

869
01:07:04,395 --> 01:07:06,813
like he said.
I've got to pinch a loaf.

870
01:07:07,023 --> 01:07:08,481
When I come back...

871
01:07:08,691 --> 01:07:10,442
this is all gone, all right?

872
01:07:59,200 --> 01:08:00,617
Do you hear that?

873
01:09:09,353 --> 01:09:10,520
Dufresne!

874
01:09:13,065 --> 01:09:14,566
Andy, let me out!

875
01:09:21,448 --> 01:09:26,411
I have no idea to this day what those
two Italian ladies were singing about.

876
01:09:26,704 --> 01:09:28,913
Truth is, I don't want to know.

877
01:09:29,123 --> 01:09:31,624
Some things are best left unsaid.

878
01:09:35,212 --> 01:09:37,922
I like to think it was something
so beautiful...

879
01:09:38,132 --> 01:09:40,258
it can't be expressed in words...

880
01:09:40,467 --> 01:09:43,386
and makes your heart ache
because of it.

881
01:09:45,055 --> 01:09:47,557
I tell you, those voices soared...

882
01:09:47,808 --> 01:09:52,103
higher and farther than anybody
in a gray place dares to dream.

883
01:09:52,313 --> 01:09:55,690
It was like a beautiful bird
flapped into our drab cage...

884
01:09:55,900 --> 01:09:58,651
and made those walls dissolve away.

885
01:09:59,111 --> 01:10:01,279
And for the briefest of moments...

886
01:10:01,488 --> 01:10:04,490
every last man at Shawshank felt free.

887
01:10:07,077 --> 01:10:09,746
It pissed the warden off
something awful.

888
01:10:11,040 --> 01:10:12,040
Open the door.

889
01:10:14,960 --> 01:10:16,711
Open it up!

890
01:10:18,005 --> 01:10:20,757
Dufresne, open this door!

891
01:10:22,092 --> 01:10:23,301
Turn that off!

892
01:10:30,351 --> 01:10:32,810
I am warning you. Turn that off!

893
01:10:50,537 --> 01:10:52,080
You're mine now.

894
01:10:59,505 --> 01:11:02,757
Andy got two weeks in the hole
for that little stunt.

895
01:11:02,967 --> 01:11:04,550
On your feet.

896
01:11:05,719 --> 01:11:08,137
- Hey, look who's here.
- Maestro!

897
01:11:09,890 --> 01:11:13,559
You couldn't play something good, huh?
Like Hank Williams?

898
01:11:13,894 --> 01:11:16,688
They broke the door down
before I could take requests.

899
01:11:16,897 --> 01:11:20,024
- Was it worth two weeks?
- Easiest time I ever did.

900
01:11:20,234 --> 01:11:24,445
- No such thing as easy time in the hole.
- A week in the hole is like a year.

901
01:11:24,655 --> 01:11:27,949
- Damn straight.
- I had Mr. Mozart to keep me company.

902
01:11:28,158 --> 01:11:31,119
So they let you tote
that record player down there, huh?

903
01:11:33,539 --> 01:11:34,914
It was in here.

904
01:11:35,749 --> 01:11:37,000
In here.

905
01:11:38,127 --> 01:11:40,211
That's the beauty of music. They...

906
01:11:40,421 --> 01:11:42,755
can't get that from you.

907
01:11:46,302 --> 01:11:48,678
Haven't you ever felt
that way about music?

908
01:11:50,472 --> 01:11:53,599
Well, I played a mean harmonica
as a younger man.

909
01:11:54,643 --> 01:11:56,352
Lost interest in it, though.

910
01:11:56,562 --> 01:11:58,146
Didn't make much sense in here.

911
01:11:58,480 --> 01:12:00,481
Here's where it makes the most sense.

912
01:12:01,025 --> 01:12:03,067
You need it so you don't forget.

913
01:12:03,652 --> 01:12:04,944
Forget?

914
01:12:05,237 --> 01:12:09,949
Forget that there are...
places...

915
01:12:10,451 --> 01:12:14,287
in the world
that aren't made out of stone.

916
01:12:15,289 --> 01:12:16,789
There's something...

917
01:12:17,124 --> 01:12:18,541
inside...

918
01:12:18,792 --> 01:12:20,752
that they can't get to...

919
01:12:20,961 --> 01:12:22,378
that they can't touch.

920
01:12:22,880 --> 01:12:24,297
That's yours.

921
01:12:25,841 --> 01:12:27,425
What are you talking about?

922
01:12:28,469 --> 01:12:32,096
Hope.

923
01:12:34,058 --> 01:12:36,059
Let me tell you something, my friend.

924
01:12:36,852 --> 01:12:39,145
Hope is a dangerous thing.

925
01:12:40,314 --> 01:12:42,648
Hope can drive a man insane.

926
01:12:43,400 --> 01:12:45,526
It's got no use on the inside.

927
01:12:45,736 --> 01:12:47,945
You'd better get used to that idea.

928
01:12:50,449 --> 01:12:51,949
Like Brooks did?

929
01:13:17,309 --> 01:13:18,309
Sit down.

930
01:13:23,649 --> 01:13:26,943
Says here that you've served
30 years of a life sentence.

931
01:13:28,112 --> 01:13:30,154
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

932
01:13:30,364 --> 01:13:31,614
Oh, yes, sir.

933
01:13:32,866 --> 01:13:34,200
Without a doubt.

934
01:13:35,369 --> 01:13:37,787
I can honestly say I'm a changed man.

935
01:13:39,790 --> 01:13:41,707
No danger to society here.

936
01:13:42,251 --> 01:13:43,793
God's honest truth.

937
01:13:46,338 --> 01:13:48,464
Absolutely rehabilitated.

938
01:13:58,434 --> 01:13:59,767
Thirty years.

939
01:14:01,728 --> 01:14:03,646
Jesus, when you say it like that...

940
01:14:04,523 --> 01:14:06,315
You wonder where it went.

941
01:14:08,735 --> 01:14:10,903
I wonder where 10 years went.

942
01:14:15,868 --> 01:14:16,909
Here.

943
01:14:17,369 --> 01:14:20,079
A little parole rejection present.

944
01:14:21,373 --> 01:14:23,040
Go ahead and open it.

945
01:14:24,168 --> 01:14:26,210
Went through one of your competitors.

946
01:14:26,378 --> 01:14:29,547
I hope you don't mind.
I wanted it to be a surprise.

947
01:14:39,558 --> 01:14:41,058
It's very pretty.

948
01:14:42,769 --> 01:14:43,978
Thank you.

949
01:14:46,565 --> 01:14:48,024
You going to play it?

950
01:14:52,571 --> 01:14:53,863
No.

951
01:14:57,451 --> 01:14:58,868
Not right now.

952
01:15:16,553 --> 01:15:17,637
Roll in!

953
01:15:53,840 --> 01:15:55,091
Lights out!

954
01:16:29,668 --> 01:16:31,836
Andy was as good as his word.

955
01:16:32,170 --> 01:16:34,964
He wrote two letters a week
instead of one.

956
01:16:37,009 --> 01:16:41,137
In 1959, the state senate
finally clued in to the fact...

957
01:16:41,346 --> 01:16:44,515
they couldn't buy him off
with just a $200 check.

958
01:16:44,683 --> 01:16:49,020
Appropriations Committee
voted an annual payment of $500...

959
01:16:49,187 --> 01:16:51,105
just to shut him up.

960
01:16:51,315 --> 01:16:54,317
And you'd be amazed how far
Andy could stretch it.

961
01:16:54,526 --> 01:16:57,445
He made deals with book clubs,
charity groups.

962
01:16:57,654 --> 01:17:00,406
He bought remaindered books
by the pound...

963
01:17:00,907 --> 01:17:02,450
Treasure Island.

964
01:17:02,993 --> 01:17:05,536
Robert Louis... Stevenson.

965
01:17:05,746 --> 01:17:07,163
Fiction, adventure.

966
01:17:09,708 --> 01:17:10,750
What's next?

967
01:17:10,917 --> 01:17:14,003
I got here Auto Repair...

968
01:17:14,713 --> 01:17:15,880
and Soap Carving.

969
01:17:16,089 --> 01:17:19,342
Trade skills and hobbies.
Under "Educational," behind you.

970
01:17:19,551 --> 01:17:21,385
Count of Monte Crisco.

971
01:17:21,887 --> 01:17:24,180
That's "Cristo," you dumb shit.

972
01:17:25,265 --> 01:17:26,265
By Alexandree...

973
01:17:26,725 --> 01:17:28,017
Dum-ass.

974
01:17:28,352 --> 01:17:29,393
Dumb-ass.

975
01:17:31,688 --> 01:17:32,730
Dumb-ass?

976
01:17:35,651 --> 01:17:37,610
Dumas. Know what that's about?

977
01:17:39,905 --> 01:17:41,906
You'd like it. It's about a prison break.

978
01:17:42,074 --> 01:17:45,951
We ought to file that
under "Educational" too, oughtn't we?

979
01:17:46,828 --> 01:17:50,915
The rest of us did our best
to pitch in when and where we could.

980
01:17:51,500 --> 01:17:53,250
By the year Kennedy was shot...

981
01:17:53,502 --> 01:17:58,005
Andy had transformed a storage room
smelling of turpentine...

982
01:17:58,298 --> 01:18:01,425
into the best prison library
in New England...

983
01:18:02,094 --> 01:18:05,054
complete with a fine selection
of Hank Williams.

984
01:18:12,437 --> 01:18:14,355
That was also when Warden Norton...

985
01:18:14,564 --> 01:18:17,483
instituted his famous
"Inside Out" program.

986
01:18:17,943 --> 01:18:20,027
You may remember reading about it.

987
01:18:20,278 --> 01:18:23,364
It made the papers
and got his picture in Look magazine.

988
01:18:23,573 --> 01:18:24,907
It's no free ride...

989
01:18:25,075 --> 01:18:28,285
but rather a genuine
progressive advance...

990
01:18:28,495 --> 01:18:30,996
in corrections and rehabilitation.

991
01:18:31,331 --> 01:18:33,874
Our inmates, properly supervised...

992
01:18:34,084 --> 01:18:36,711
will be put to work
outside these walls...

993
01:18:36,920 --> 01:18:40,005
performing all manner
of public service.

994
01:18:40,173 --> 01:18:42,967
These men can learn the value
of an honest day's labor...

995
01:18:43,176 --> 01:18:46,971
while providing a valuable service
to the community...

996
01:18:47,180 --> 01:18:51,892
and at a bare minimum of expense
to Mr. and Mrs. John Q. Taxpayer.

997
01:18:52,310 --> 01:18:54,645
Of course he didn't tell the press...

998
01:18:54,855 --> 01:18:58,315
that "bare minimum of expense"
is a fairly loose term.

999
01:18:58,525 --> 01:19:01,569
There are 100 different ways
to skim off the top.

1000
01:19:01,778 --> 01:19:04,280
Men, materials, you name it.

1001
01:19:04,614 --> 01:19:07,491
And oh, my Lord,
how the money rolled in!

1002
01:19:07,701 --> 01:19:10,244
At this rate,
you'll put me out of business.

1003
01:19:10,454 --> 01:19:14,874
With this pool of slave labor,
you can underbid any contractor in town.

1004
01:19:15,459 --> 01:19:18,419
We're providing
a valuable community service.

1005
01:19:18,628 --> 01:19:22,298
That's fine for the papers,
but I've got a family to feed.

1006
01:19:24,968 --> 01:19:26,510
We go back a long way.

1007
01:19:27,804 --> 01:19:32,725
I need this highway contract. I don't
get it and I go under. That's a fact.

1008
01:19:33,643 --> 01:19:35,436
You have some of this fine pie...

1009
01:19:35,687 --> 01:19:39,023
my missus made for you.
You think about that.

1010
01:19:47,282 --> 01:19:49,992
I wouldn't worry too much
about this contract.

1011
01:19:50,202 --> 01:19:53,287
It seems to me I already got my boys
committed elsewhere.

1012
01:19:55,248 --> 01:19:58,334
You be sure and thank Maisie
for this fine pie.

1013
01:19:59,419 --> 01:20:01,587
And behind every shady deal...

1014
01:20:01,922 --> 01:20:04,548
behind every dollar earned...

1015
01:20:04,841 --> 01:20:07,885
